This data contribution is a compilation of low-temperature apatite fission track (AFT) and (U-Th)/He thermochronology data from published (historical and current) and new unpublished sources. The regional scope of this data contribution is roughly the southern Rocky Mountains of New Mexico, Colorado and Wyoming with scattered data from surrounding Great Plains, northern plains and Colorado Plateau sites.

The purpose of this data contribution is to compile and provide easy access to published low-temperature thermochronologic data drawn from journal articles, student theses and dissertations, and new samples circa mid- 2014

These data are made available through New Mexico's Experimental Program to Stimulate Competitive Research (NM EPSCoR) data portal. The portal provides access to data generated by and of use to the EPSCoR community including researchers, educators, and policy leaders, as well as the general public.

These are baseline data on the metabolic effects of culture density in semicontinuous cultures grown in PSI photobioreactors.

This is a test of three things: 1) functionality of photobioreactors from PSI, 2) effect of cell density on metabolism, 3) the interaction between temperature, cell density and metabolism. This is a baseline for comparison to encapsulated cultures.

Conducted in the lab of Martin Jonikas at Stanford's Carnegie Institute. These data are made available through New Mexico's Experimental Program to Stimulate Competitive Research (NM EPSCoR) data portal. The portal provides access to data generated by and of use to the EPSCoR community including researchers, educators, and policy leaders, as well as the general public.

This data set represents chemical water analyses for waters relevant to geothermal research in New Mexico. It includes parameters such as temperature, salinity, and major ion composition in addition to selected trace elements and isotopic characteristics.

Water chemistry is used to understand the origin and flow path of waters, and particular geochemical characteristics are used to predict temperature of geothermal resources, the extent of mixing of groundwater fluids, and when geochemical changes through time are available, resource sustainability.

These data are made available through New Mexico's Experimental Program to Stimulate Competitive Research (NM EPSCoR) data portal. The portal provides access to data generated by and of use to the EPSCoR community including researchers, educators, and policy leaders, as well as the general public.

These are baseline data on the metabolic effects of culture density in semicontinuous cultures grown in PSI photobioreactors.

This is a test of three things: 1) functionality of photobioreactors from PSI, 2) effect of cell density on metabolism, 3) the interaction between temperature, cell density and metabolism. This is a baseline for comparison to encapsulated cultures.

Conducted in the lab of Martin Jonikas at Stanford's Carnegie Institute. These data are made available through New Mexico's Experimental Program to Stimulate Competitive Research (NM EPSCoR) data portal. The portal provides access to data generated by and of use to the EPSCoR community including researchers, educators, and policy leaders, as well as the general public.
